			<title>Drive Mappings/DNS problem</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76821-Drive-Mappings-DNS-problem&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Thu, 22 May 2014 15:55:55 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Back in July after my office moved, our DNS settings changed internally. 
Now instead of pulling our DNS from a local(on-site) server, we get it from a globally sourced block of DNS information based on region. 
It's supposed to allow for failover and redundancy but thus far I haven't noticed any...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Back in July after my office moved, our DNS settings changed internally.<br />
Now instead of pulling our DNS from a local(on-site) server, we get it from a globally sourced block of DNS information based on region.<br />
It's supposed to allow for failover and redundancy but thus far I haven't noticed any positive gains.<br />
<br />
In December, 95% of my office (~25 people) got all new laptops.<br />
Most of those people now alternate telecommuting and car commuting.<br />
<br />
When most of those people get into the office after having worked from home, they have the most bizarre problem:<br />
<br />
All of the network drives that point to local servers will not connect.<br />
You cannot ping those servers via domain name or IP address.<br />
You can get external and internal internet sources but going to any local server won't work.<br />
Outlook works, which makes sense because the Outlook servers are non-local.<br />
<br />
In about half of the cases, simply waiting 10-15 minutes allows the drives to &quot;connect silently&quot; and they spontaneously start working.<br />
<br />
Thus far I have had three different troubleshooting paths:<br />
1 - Reboot.  This'll usually work.<br />
2 - Run CMD - ipconfig /release /flushdns /renew  (without flushdns it won't work.)  This works in about a third of the remaining cases.  (I've created a batch file for this.)<br />
3 - Remap the drives.  This works in about a third of the remaining cases.<br />
<br />
If it doesn't work at all, you simply need to wait.<br />
<br />
With Dale's assistance I was able to cobble together a batch file that will remap the drives of the users.<br />
Unfortunately due to the fact that, try as I did when we undertook the server move in July, there is no longer any standardization on the drive mappings due to the respective needs of each department.  This means that a single catch-all batch file won't work.<br />
I've started the process of making custom batch files for each user.  This isn't too bad, as there's only ~40 people to worry about.<br />
<br />
However the development manager got into his head that we should be using Powershell for this.<br />
While I am aware of the PS commands to map a drive (in PS and persistently in Windows) I've not been able to figure out a way to have PS grab the paths and drive IDs for the existing mappings, store them as variables, kill the existing drive mappings, then remap using the stored information.<br />
<br />
<b>**tl/dr** Is there a way to use Powershell to:<br />
1 - Grab the drive letters and UNC paths of existing drives<br />
2 - Kill the existing drive letters<br />
3 - Remap (persistently) those drive letters using the stored UNC paths<br />
4 - Profit ... ?</b><br />
<br />
Thanks</div>

]]></content:encoded>
