			<title>YAML for program inputs</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76769-YAML-for-program-inputs&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Tue, 06 May 2014 13:29:57 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Not a tech support request, more of a hobby house thing just technical.  Probably only MI will read this, if that :P  
 
I'm migrating to using yaml (http://www.yaml.org/) whenever I want to write something down in a data structure that will be parsed be a computer program, and may wind up being...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Not a tech support request, more of a hobby house thing just technical.  Probably only MI will read this, if that :P <br />
<br />
I'm migrating to using <a href="http://www.yaml.org/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">yaml</a> whenever I want to write something down in a data structure that will be parsed be a computer program, and may wind up being too complex for standard &quot;key = value&quot; formats like ini, and a spreadsheet format isn't what I want either.  For example, a list of monsters and attributes for an RPG.<br />
<br />
Essentially:  <br />
<br />
XML is meant for <i>documents</i>, not data or configuration.  It's verbose and complex to parse.<br />
<br />
INI and similar formats lack support for lists, trees, dictionaries, and other advanced/nested data structures.<br />
<br />
CSV, like INI, doesn't directly support nested data structures.<br />
<br />
Lisp is mostly only used by people writing lisp.<br />
<br />
JSON is meant as a data interchange format and offers no &quot;human writing&quot; advantages over native code.  JSON is so bare-bones it doesn't even support comments.<br />
<br />
YAML solves the same problems as JSON, but its grammar is substantially more complex and the result is a format that is far more easy to write than JSON, while still being about as easy to parse.  Yaml also has some (admittedly ugly) support for some non-standard data structures like the Python &quot;tuple.&quot;  The main tradeoff of yaml compared to JSON is that there can be multiple ways to specify the same thing, and it's easier to accidentally write valid yaml that doesn't mean what you thought it meant (for example, getting a nested list when you expected a single list).  That also means automatically generated yaml might not look the same as equivalent yaml you would write yourself.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
